        </p>

        <h2>The Problem with the 7-Year Rule</h2>
        
        <p>The traditional 7-year rule assumes that dogs age at a constant rate throughout their lives, with each dog year equivalent to 7 human years. This simplistic calculation fails to account for several critical factors:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Rapid early development:</strong> Dogs mature much faster in their first two years than the 7-year rule suggests</li>
          <li><strong>Breed size variations:</strong> Small dogs typically live longer than large dogs, aging at different rates</li>
          <li><strong>Non-linear aging patterns:</strong> Dogs don't age consistently throughout their lives</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>The Science Behind Modern Age Calculation</h2>

        <p>Contemporary veterinary research has revealed that dog aging follows a more complex pattern. The American Veterinary Medical Association now recommends this approach:</p>

